  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Insufficient Income Documentation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The most common rejection reason. You need 6 full months of bank statements showing €3,295+ average income. Three months won't work. Inconsistent income raises flags. Provide clear, comprehensive financial records.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing Apostille on Criminal Record</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Your criminal record certificate must be apostilled by your home country authorities. A regular police check isn't enough. This process can take 2-4 weeks—start early.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Unclear Foreign Income Source</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must prove your work is for foreign (non-Croatian) companies or clients. Contracts should clearly show the foreign company's registration and location. Vague "freelance work" descriptions get rejected.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Insurance Not Covering Full Stay</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Your health insurance must cover the entire requested visa duration (up to 18 months). Policies expiring mid-stay are rejected. Get annual coverage or ensure renewal is seamless.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Consecutive Renewal is Possible</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Unlike most visas, Croatia's Digital Nomad permit cannot be renewed back-to-back. You must leave Croatia for 6 months before reapplying. Plan accordingly if you want to stay longer than 18 months.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Croatia -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Croatia</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Croatia has a decent healthcare system with both public and private options. As a digital nomad visa holder, you won't have access to the public system (HZZO) and will rely on your private health insurance for all medical care.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Quality</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Strengths</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ Good quality private clinics in cities</li>
          <li>✓ Many doctors speak English</li>
          <li>✓ Modern facilities in Zagreb and Split</li>
          <li>✓ Affordable private care costs</li>
          <li>✓ Dental tourism destination (low costs)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Considerations</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Public system has long wait times</li>
          <li>• Smaller towns have limited facilities</li>
          <li>• Some specialists only in Zagreb</li>
          <li>• Emergency services can be basic outside cities</li>
          <li>• Must pay out-of-pocket, then claim</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Accessing Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Private Clinics</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Poliklinika (polyclinics) offer private healthcare services. You'll typically pay out-of-pocket (€50-150 for GP visit, €80-200 for specialist) and submit receipts to your insurance for reimbursement.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Pharmacies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Ljekarna (pharmacies) are common in all towns. Many medications available over-the-counter in Croatia require prescriptions elsewhere. Pharmacists often speak English and can advise on minor ailments.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Emergencies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 194 for ambulance or 112 for general emergency. Hospital emergency departments (Hitna pomoć) will treat everyone regardless of insurance. Present your insurance information for billing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Dental opportunity:</strong> Croatia is a dental tourism destination with high-quality care at 50-70% lower costs than Western Europe. Consider scheduling dental work during your stay—even out-of-pocket costs are often cheaper than insured treatment elsewhere.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Croatia's Digital Nomad Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          As of 2025, you need approximately €3,295/month (about 2.5 times the Croatian average salary). This amounts to €39,540 for a 12-month stay or €59,310 for the full 18-month period. Add 10% for each dependent family member.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I pay taxes in Croatia on my freelance income?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Digital nomad visa holders are exempt from Croatian income tax on foreign-sourced earnings. Your income is only taxed in your country of tax residence (if any). However, you should verify your home country's rules about worldwide income and tax residency.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I renew the Digital Nomad Visa after 18 months?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not directly. You cannot renew consecutively—you must leave Croatia for at least 6 months before reapplying. Many nomads rotate to other countries (Portugal, Spain, etc.) during this gap period, then return to Croatia with a fresh application.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is SafetyWing accepted for Croatia's visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, SafetyWing Nomad Insurance is widely accepted and commonly used by digital nomads in Croatia. Ensure your policy explicitly covers Croatia and spans your entire intended stay. For longer stays, comprehensive international insurance may provide better coverage.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work for Croatian clients on this visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The Digital Nomad Visa is exclusively for income from foreign sources. You cannot work for Croatian companies or provide services to Croatian clients. Violating this could jeopardize your visa status.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is the approval rate only 41.5%?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Common rejection reasons include insufficient income documentation, missing or improper documents, unclear proof of foreign employment, and failure to meet the income threshold consistently. Thorough preparation significantly improves your chances.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

